title: Want To Buy:  or Trade for Sig P250C 9mm X-Change
postcontent:
I have a P250C in .40 S&W.  It is a good gun and a good caliber.  It is my nightstand gun (just in case someone gets past the massive dog).  My wife's nightstand gun is a P250SC. 

Anybody familiar with the P250 doesn't need to read this paragraph.  He or she knows that the Fire Control Group is the numbered part of the gun.  A shooter can change the slide/barrel combination anywhere from .380, 9mm, .40 S&W or .45 ACP in profiles ranging from a subcompact through a full size.  The same with the grip assembly.  

I'd like to trade the .40 slide, barrel, grip and 2 magazines (The gun is usually sold with one).  The mags are marked with glow-in-the-dark paint so they can be located in the dark and to make sure I don't drop a 9mm mag in my .40.

As a trade, Since we are exchanging two things of roughly equal value, it should be pretty close to an even trade.  If you only have one mag for your 9mm kit, I'd like some sort of consideration for the fact that you'll be receiving two.  If there is something that makes your 9mm kit better in some way (holster, or something), I could make the difference up in ammo that you're going to want so you can get to the range as soon as possible.  If we end up making this deal on a Sunday afternoon while the weather's still nice, I'll pay for a day pass at the Deer-Creek shooting range so you can get shooting that day.

I have looked for these kits and they are around.  If somebody bought a 2-Sum kit and would like a second, more powerful caliber, this deal's for you!  I know what the price of one of these kits would be if I was to buy it new.  have a kit you'd like to sell, please let me know how much you want and we'll go from there.

For Sale One Smith & Wesson .460V 5” Barrel With Genuine S&W Leather Holster.  This gun has sold for the asking price,  I will leave this up for a day or two because I know a lot of you were following it.  Thank you all for your interest.  Sincerely, Gary...

I bought this gun new & while it has not had a lot of ammo put through it, it has seen a lot of time on my hip. It has a few little (lite) scratches, in my opinion nothing significant for a carry gun. The gun is very accurate, I’m a pretty decent shot & while I had a Leupold 4X scope on it I could shoot a 3” group from a rest at 100 yards! One of the real nice things about the .460 is that you have so many ammunition choices!  You can shoot .45 Colt, which is a pretty tame round in this revolver, or you can step it up to .454 Casull, or go all the way to the .460 S&W MAGNUM! You are looking at “The Worlds Most Versatile Big Bore Revolver!” The sights are fully adjustable for Windage & Elevation! This is a real sweet gun, it’s powerful enough to keep you safe in the woods & to do what ever you ask of it in that area, yet small enough so as not to get in the way of everyday activities when out in the bush. And really, if you can’t kill it with a .460, you probably won’t be able to kill it with a .500! Also you have so many more ammo options within each bullet group, plink with the 45 colt & if the recoil of the the .460 S&W MAGNUM leaves you wondering why you bought such a monster, then you can always step it down to the .454 Casull which is by no means a slouch!  I don’t know why anyone would even look at a .500, if you buy a .500 you shoot .500’s & nothing else, and if the recoil is to much for you, then that’s just tough, that’s what your stuck with!
